**11. What is CSS and how is it applied to a webpage?** 
CSS stands for Cascading Style Sheets. It is used to design the colors, fonts, and layout of a 
webpage. It makes the plain HTML structure look beau ful and professional. You can apply CSS 
to an HTML page in three different ways. These ways are inline styles, internal style tags, and 
external CSS files. External files are the best choice for big website projects. 
**12. Explain the CSS box model.** 
The CSS box model is a box that wraps around every single HTML element. It consists of four 
dis nct layers from the inside to the outside. These layers are the content, padding, border, and 
margin. The content is the actual text or image on the screen. Padding is the inner space, while 
border surrounds the padding layer. Margin is the outermost space that separates elements 
from each other. 
**13. What is the difference between margin and padding?** 
Padding is the space inside an element, between the content and the border. It makes the 
background area around the text look larger and cleaner. Margin is the empty space completely 
outside the element's border. It creates distance between different HTML boxes on the 
webpage layout. Padding affects the size inside the box, but margin affects the outside area. 
Both are very important for controlling spacing in web design. 
**14. Explain CSS specificity.** 
CSS specificity is a set of rules that the browser uses to choose styles. If two different CSS rules 
target the same element, the browser calculates scores. The rule with the highest specificity 
score wins and changes the element. Inline styles have the highest score of all. ID selectors are 
stronger than class selectors, and tag selectors are the weakest. It helps resolve conflicts when 
mul ple styles are wri en for one item. 
**15. What is the difference between class selectors and ID selectors?** 
A class selector can be used on mul ple elements across the webpage. You target a class name 
in CSS by wri ng a dot symbol before it. An ID selector is unique and can only be used on one 
single element per page. You target an ID in CSS by using a hashtag symbol before it. Class 
selectors are great for reusable styles like bu on designs. ID selectors are best for unique layout 
sec ons like a naviga on bar. 
**16. What are pseudo-classes in CSS?** 
Pseudo-classes are keywords added to selectors that describe a special state of an element. For 
example, the :hover pseudo-class changes the style when a mouse moves over it. Another 
example is :focus, which styles an element when a user clicks inside an input. There is also :nth
child, which selects specific items in a list. They help make websites feel interac ve without 
using any complex JavaScript code. 
**17. What are pseudo-elements in CSS?** 
Pseudo-elements are keywords used to style specific parts of an HTML element. They are 
wri en with two colons, such as ::before or ::a er. You can use them to add extra decora ve 
content before or a er a text. Another example is ::first-le er, which changes only the first le er 
of a paragraph. They do not create real new HTML tags in the DOM tree. They are very useful 
for advanced CSS design techniques. 
**18. Explain the purpose of the posi on property.** 
The posi on property defines how an element sits on a webpage layout. It allows developers to 
move elements away from their normal document flow. You can use it to create overlapping 
designs or floa ng ac on bu ons. It works together with helper proper es like top, bo om, 
le , and right. Without it, elements just follow a simple ver cal or horizontal order. It gives 
