**20. Explain how Flexbox works.** 
Flexbox stands for Flexible Box Layout. It is a layout system used to arrange items easily in a 
single row or column. It automa cally calculates the space and size of items inside its parent 
container. It makes alignment very easy, even when the screen size changes dynamically. It is 
called a one-dimensional system because it works in one direc on at a me. It solved many old 
layout problems in web development history. 
**21. What are the main proper es of a Flex container?** 
The main container proper es control how items are arranged inside a flexbox layout. The 
property display: flex ac vates the flexbox system on the parent element. The flex-direc on 
property decides if items go horizontally in rows or ver cally in columns. The jus fy-content 
property aligns the items along the main axis line. The align-items property controls the 
alignment on the cross axis side. Finally, flex-wrap allows items to move to a new line if space is 
small. 
**22. Explain CSS Grid and its advantages.** 
CSS Grid is a powerful layout system for webpages that uses columns and rows together. It is a 
two-dimensional system, meaning it controls both horizontal and ver cal spaces. The main 
advantage is that it makes big layout sec ons very easy to build. You can create complex grid 
lines and place items anywhere inside them. It reduces the need for complex margins and old 
floa ng elements in code. It is perfect for newspaper layouts or modern dashboard interfaces. 
**23. What are media queries and why are they used?** 
Media queries are filters in CSS that apply styles based on device characteris cs. They can check 
things like screen maximum width, height, or screen resolu on. They are used to change the 
website layout for smartphones, tablets, and computers. For example, a three-column layout 
can become one column on small phone screens. Without them, desktop websites would look 
too ny and unreadable on mobile devices. They are the core technology behind responsive 
web design prac ces. 
**24. What is responsive web design?** 
Responsive web design is a method to make webpages look great on all devices. It means the 
website automa cally adjusts its layout for phones, tablets, and desktop monitors. It uses 
flexible grid systems, flexible images, and media queries to achieve this goal. This ensures a 
good user experience for everyone, no ma er their screen size. It eliminates the need to build 
separate websites for mobile and desktop users. It is an industry-standard requirement for all 
modern web developers. 
**25. Explain the difference between display: none and visibility: hidden.** 
The rule display: none completely removes the element from the website layout structure. The 
webpage acts as if that element does not exist at all, taking up zero space. The rule visibility: 
hidden only hides the element from the eyes of the user. However, the element s ll stays in the 
layout and takes up its normal empty space. Use display: none when you want to hide menus 
completely. Use visibility: hidden when you want to keep the layout space intact. 
**26. What is the purpose of CSS transi ons?** 
CSS transi ons allow you to change style property values smoothly over a specific me. Instead 
